<br>
What's clear about Bush's war strategy is that it loses focus and initiative when it comes to dealing with the aftermath of bombing its target into the stone age.  We are already having tremedous problems dealing with the increasingly organized resistance to our presence in Afghanistan and Iraq.  We face unprecedented buget deficits and the largest national debt in our history - all brought about in the three short years of Bush's regime, though he is STILL trying to somehow blame Clinton for it - and Lord George is now targeting another third world country for intervention and regime change.  <br>
<br>
Cog, I find your anti-christ statement rather interesting in this context.  What worries me most about Bush is that he is an openly Born-again Christian, who panders to the religious right as much as he can possibly get away with.  It has been said of him repeatedly that he is a true believer, and that this truly dictates his policies.  Given the increasingly negative long term effects of his policies, I keep wondering if he is simply waiting for the second coming. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=366694">Nayl</a>
